=== Ch4_Intro ===
Chapter 4: Preparing children for a digital future. # diagram: digital_literacy.jpg

This chapter covers digital and media literacy—the thing that experts agree actually works for protecting children online.

It's Chapter 4. Out of 5.

*   [What does that tell us?]
    -> Ch4_Structure

=== Ch4_Structure ===
Structure reveals priority.

The consultation spends three chapters on bans, restrictions, and enforcement before getting to education. This isn't accidental—it's a statement about what the government considers primary (restrictions) and what it considers supplementary (education).

The consultation never asks: "Should we invest in education and digital literacy INSTEAD of age restrictions?" Only "What education should ACCOMPANY the restrictions?"

The framing assumes restrictions are the main course. Education is the garnish.

*   [Show me the questions.]
    -> Ch4_Q52

=== Ch4_Q52 ===
Question 52 asks:

"Which areas of media or digital literacy do children and families most need additional help with?"

The options include: managing screen time, spotting AI content, keeping information private, online behaviour, checking information, understanding algorithms, staying safe, reporting content, knowing age-appropriate apps.

*   [What's the problem?]
    -> Ch4_Q52_Analysis

=== Ch4_Q52_Analysis ===
This is actually a decent question—but the "additional" is doing a lot of work.

"Additional" implies that existing support is a baseline to build on. In reality, youth services funding fell 72% between 2010 and 2024. The government's own community media literacy funding is £2 million—trivial compared to the enforcement costs of age verification infrastructure.

If you think digital literacy should be the primary approach—not a supplement to bans—this is where you say so. But you'll need to use free-text boxes elsewhere to make that case, because this question only asks WHAT to teach, not WHETHER education should be the priority.

*   [What about the support questions?]
    -> Ch4_Q53_56

=== Ch4_Q53_56 ===
Questions 53-56 ask where people get help with online safety, where they'd like more support, and how the government could better support children outside schools.

These are genuinely useful questions. Schools, libraries, youth clubs, community centres, faith groups, online resources—the consultation recognises that education happens everywhere, not just in classrooms.

Q56 specifically asks about children with additional needs—SEND, communication difficulties, learning differences. This is one of the better-designed questions in the consultation.

*   [What about high-quality content?]
    -> Ch4_Q57

=== Ch4_Q57 ===
Questions 57-59 ask about "high quality online content" for children:

"Who would you trust to determine what is 'high quality' online content for children aged 13-16?"

Government / Platform teams / Parents / Children / Developmental experts / Educators / Youth workers / Charities.

*   [What's the concern here?]
    -> Ch4_Q57_Analysis

=== Ch4_Q57_Analysis ===
The question assumes someone should be determining what counts as "high quality" content. That's content curation by authority—a short step from content control.

Who decides what's "high quality"? If it's the government, you've got state-approved content for children. If it's platforms, you've got corporate curation. If it's "experts," which experts? The ones who think all screen time is harmful, or the ones who distinguish between types of use?

Q59 asks how this would work in practice. If you think defining and promoting "high quality content" risks becoming content censorship, say so.

